  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. How are ratings distributed?\n",
    "\n",
    "Ratings run from 0.5 to 5.0 stars. Knowing the distribution matters: if almost\n",
    "everyone gives 4–5 stars, then \"predicting a high rating\" is easy and we need to\n",
    "be careful about how we measure success later."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Average rating: 3.5\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = sns.countplot(data=ratings, x=\"rating\", color=\"steelblue\")\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Distribution of movie ratings\")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Rating (stars)\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Number of ratings\")\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Average rating:\", round(ratings[\"rating\"].mean(), 2))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. How active are users? How popular are movies?\n",
    "\n",
    "Recommenders live or die by this. A handful of \"super-users\" rate thousands of\n",
    "movies, while most users rate only a few. Likewise, a few blockbusters get tons\n",
    "of ratings while most movies get almost none. This **long-tail** pattern is\n",
    "everywhere in real-world data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x400 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Median ratings per user:  70\n",
      "Median ratings per movie: 3\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ratings_per_user = ratings.groupby(\"userId\").size()\n",
    "ratings_per_movie = ratings.groupby(\"movieId\").size()\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].hist(ratings_per_user, bins=50, color=\"steelblue\")\n",
    "axes[0].set_title(\"Ratings per user\")\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel(\"# ratings\")\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel(\"# users\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].hist(ratings_per_movie, bins=50, color=\"indianred\")\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(\"Ratings per movie\")\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel(\"# ratings\")\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel(\"# movies\")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Median ratings per user:  {int(ratings_per_user.median())}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Median ratings per movie: {int(ratings_per_movie.median())}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. What are the most-rated movies?\n",
    "\n",
    "We join (`merge`) the rating counts back to the movie titles so the result is\n",
    "human-readable. \"Most rated\" is our first hint at a **popularity baseline** —\n",
    "the simplest possible recommender."
   ]
  },
