   ],
   "source": [
    "movie_stats = (\n",
    "    ratings.groupby(\"movieId\")\n",
    "    .agg(num_ratings=(\"rating\", \"size\"), avg_rating=(\"rating\", \"mean\"))\n",
    "    .merge(movies[[\"movieId\", \"title\"]], on=\"movieId\")\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "top_rated = movie_stats.sort_values(\"num_ratings\", ascending=False).head(10)\n",
    "top_rated[[\"title\", \"num_ratings\", \"avg_rating\"]].round(2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. How sparse is the data?\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine a giant grid: one row per user, one column per movie. Most cells are\n",
    "**empty** because no one watches every movie. The fraction of filled cells is\n",
    "the **density**; `1 - density` is the **sparsity**. Real recommender data is\n",
    "typically >98% sparse — this is the central challenge the models must overcome."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Users x Movies grid: 610 x 9,724 = 5,931,640 cells\n",
      "Actual ratings:      100,836\n",
      "Density:   1.70%  (fraction of cells filled)\n",
      "Sparsity: 98.30%  (fraction of cells empty)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "n_users = ratings[\"userId\"].nunique()\n",
    "n_movies = ratings[\"movieId\"].nunique()\n",
    "n_ratings = len(ratings)\n",
    "\n",
    "density = n_ratings / (n_users * n_movies)\n",
    "print(f\"Users x Movies grid: {n_users:,} x {n_movies:,} = {n_users * n_movies:,} cells\")\n",
    "print(f\"Actual ratings:      {n_ratings:,}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Density:  {density:6.2%}  (fraction of cells filled)\")\n",
    "print(f\"Sparsity: {1 - density:6.2%}  (fraction of cells empty)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## What we learned & what's next\n",
    "\n",
    "Jot down your takeaways here (recruiters love seeing your reasoning):\n",
    "\n",
    "- Ratings skew toward **3–4 stars** — people tend to rate things they like.\n",
    "- Both users and movies follow a **long tail** — a few are very active/popular.\n",
    "- The data is extremely **sparse**, so our models must generalize from few signals.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Next stage:** build a **popularity baseline** recommender, then improve on it\n",
    "with content-based and collaborative-filtering models.",
   ]
  }
